00:31:34,614 --> 00:31:37,576
Again, commitment to quality.

625
00:31:37,576 --> 00:31:38,036
Now...

626
00:31:39,003 --> 00:31:41,065
I'd like to talk about planning, and...

627
00:31:41,065 --> 00:31:43,148
Okay, I hear you guys.

628
00:31:43,148 --> 00:31:45,251
Ah, this guy's not gonna talk to us about planning, really?

629
00:31:45,251 --> 00:31:45,411
Okay.

630
00:31:45,411 --> 00:31:48,054
The reason why I wanna talk about planning is because this is...

631
00:31:48,054 --> 00:31:49,556
Depending on how you do your planning, I think...

632
00:31:49,556 --> 00:31:55,023
I think it can be a great tool to really build a strong team that is united.

633
00:31:55,023 --> 00:31:55,343
And...

634
00:31:56,734 --> 00:31:57,935
I'm going to explain this.

635
00:31:57,935 --> 00:32:01,537
So first of all, we do sprints during production.

636
00:32:01,537 --> 00:32:03,158
They're two-week sprints, very flexible.

637
00:32:03,158 --> 00:32:04,979
We do two-week sprints because we

638
00:32:04,979 --> 00:32:07,280
want to be synchronized with the rest of the production floor.

639
00:32:07,280 --> 00:32:09,181
It's also nice when we have play tests every two weeks

640
00:32:09,181 --> 00:32:10,902
because we're synchronized.

641
00:32:10,902 --> 00:32:14,284
And because, honestly, if you have two-week sprints,

642
00:32:14,284 --> 00:32:15,785
you have a small list of tasks.

643
00:32:15,785 --> 00:32:18,626
And for the people working on their tasks,

644
00:32:18,626 --> 00:32:20,607
it feels like it's always achievable.

645
00:32:20,607 --> 00:32:22,388
As opposed to having, for example, four weeks,

646
00:32:22,388 --> 00:32:23,289
we have this huge list.

647
00:32:23,289 --> 00:32:25,070
And it always feels like, oh, I've got to do all this, man.

648
00:32:26,471 --> 00:32:28,612
The second thing is aim for 11-12 days of work.

649
00:32:28,612 --> 00:32:30,574
That's just a formula. Don't worry too much about it.

650
00:32:30,574 --> 00:32:33,896
Essentially, when we plan, we always round up.

651
00:32:33,896 --> 00:32:36,999
So if we think something's gonna take half a day,

652
00:32:36,999 --> 00:32:38,300
we'll put one day.

653
00:32:38,300 --> 00:32:39,320
If we think something's gonna take 3.5-4 days,

654
00:32:39,320 --> 00:32:40,682
we'll put five days.

655
00:32:40,682 --> 00:32:41,402
And we add up to 11-12 days,

656
00:32:41,402 --> 00:32:43,163
and that's how we do our planning.

657
00:32:43,163 --> 00:32:45,185
So I know some people like to do, for example,

658
00:32:45,185 --> 00:32:47,066
realistic estimates and multiply by 2,

659
00:32:47,066 --> 00:32:47,707
multiply by 1.5.

660
00:32:47,707 --> 00:32:49,969
If you're struggling with your formula,

661
00:32:49,969 --> 00:32:52,771
maybe try this one, maybe not.

662
00:32:52,771 --> 00:32:55,113
When we manage our sprint, when we planify...

663
00:32:56,307 --> 00:32:58,909
when we planify, plan our sprints.

664
00:32:58,909 --> 00:33:00,670
We like to, planify, nice.

665
00:33:00,670 --> 00:33:04,272
We like to synchronize the various trades.

666
00:33:04,272 --> 00:33:05,773
Again, this is very easy for us

667
00:33:05,773 --> 00:33:07,094
because everyone's under the same roof

668
00:33:07,094 --> 00:33:08,315
and we do the planning for everyone.

669
00:33:08,315 --> 00:33:11,897
For example, if you want to add a new weapon,

670
00:33:11,897 --> 00:33:14,058
you probably want your artist to model

671
00:33:14,058 --> 00:33:15,419
at least the first pass of the weapon

672
00:33:15,419 --> 00:33:17,360
and then you can have programming and animator

673
00:33:17,360 --> 00:33:19,342
do a pass maybe the next week or something.

674
00:33:19,342 --> 00:33:20,562
But this becomes super easy.

675
00:33:21,203 --> 00:33:24,985
Again, de-risking first, always de-risking first.

676
00:33:24,985 --> 00:33:28,527
And lastly, the priority is always to unblock your coworkers.

677
00:33:28,527 --> 00:33:29,647
So we do, we do have goals, right?

678
00:33:29,647 --> 00:33:32,448
This is the things that we'd like to hit this sprint.

679
00:33:32,448 --> 00:33:34,049
But regardless of whatever you're working on,

680
00:33:34,049 --> 00:33:36,951
you're taskless, if one of your coworkers is blocked,

681
00:33:36,951 --> 00:33:38,111
you want to unblock him.

682
00:33:38,111 --> 00:33:41,993
So again, I have my animator right next to me,

683
00:33:41,993 --> 00:33:44,514
and he's blocked and he's trying to do something.

684
00:33:44,514 --> 00:33:46,155
He's like, eh, I need code support for this.

685
00:33:46,155 --> 00:33:46,756
Okay, no problem.

686
00:33:46,756 --> 00:33:47,916
And I'll just shove whatever I'm doing,

687
00:33:47,916 --> 00:33:49,757
as long as it's not, like, too complicated process.

688
00:33:50,678 --> 00:33:53,439
I'll give you what you need, and then he gets unblocked.

689
00:33:53,439 --> 00:33:55,820
And the great thing about this is this is a great

690
00:33:55,820 --> 00:33:57,940
team building and team spirit thing, right?

691
00:33:57,940 --> 00:34:01,341
Where it, it really feels like your coworkers have your back.

692
00:34:01,341 --> 00:34:05,342
So when you help your friend, you unblock him the next time around,

693
00:34:05,342 --> 00:34:07,903
like he gets unblocked, or you unblock somebody else,

694
00:34:07,903 --> 00:34:11,624
and this is a great way to, to really handle this.

695
00:34:11,624 --> 00:34:15,604
Now, now is this guy really gonna talk to us about bug tracking?

